{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612253"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:21:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:21:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16269"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16269"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.03,0.24,0.06,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8960"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64585"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8960"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16269"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50019"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5119"},{"type":"tags","id":"5247"},{"type":"tags","id":"7061"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8499"},{"type":"tags","id":"10114"},{"type":"tags","id":"10115"},{"type":"tags","id":"10676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21327"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22400"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64585"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His testicular volume is 4 mL bilaterally with minimal pubic hair growth, consistent with early puberty.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following hormonal changes is primarily responsible for the initial testicular enlargement?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["FSH stimulation","FSH inhibition","LH stimulation","LH inhibition","Testosterone stimulation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early male puberty (Tanner stages 1-2), testicular enlargement occurs primarily due to seminiferous tubule growth. \u003Cstrong\u003EFSH stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for this initial change through its effects on Sertoli cell proliferation and seminiferous tubule development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFSH inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E would prevent normal pubertal development and testicular growth. FSH is essential for initiating and maintaining spermatogenesis through its effects on Sertoli cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELH stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E, while important for testosterone production from Leydig cells, is not the primary driver of initial testicular enlargement. LH becomes more important in later stages of puberty for secondary sexual characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELH inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E would impair testosterone production but is not directly related to the initial testicular size increase seen in early puberty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETestosterone stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E is a consequence of LH stimulation of Leydig cells and becomes more important in later stages of puberty. It is not the primary driver of initial testicular enlargement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increase in testicular size from approximately 3 mL to 4-6 mL marks the onset of puberty. This occurs due to FSH-mediated Sertoli cell proliferation and seminiferous tubule development, before significant testosterone production begins.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["FSH stimulates Sertoli cell proliferation and seminiferous tubule growth during early puberty.","Testicular enlargement is the first physical sign of male puberty, occurring at Tanner Stage 1-2.","Sertoli cells are essential for spermatogenesis and respond primarily to FSH stimulation."],"references":["O\u0027Shaughnessy PJ, Monteiro A, Verhoeven G, De Gendt K, Abel MH. Effect of FSH on testicular morphology and spermatogenesis in gonadotrophin-deficient hypogonadal mice lacking androgen receptors. Reproduction. 2010 Jan;139(1):177-84. doi: 10.1530/REP-09-0377. PMID: 19846485; PMCID: PMC2791495.","Santi D, Cr\u00e9pieux P, Reiter E, Spaggiari G, Brigante G, Casarini L, Rochira V, Simoni M. Follicle-stimulating Hormone (FSH) Action on Spermatogenesis: A Focus on Physiological and Therapeutic Roles. J Clin Med. 2020 Apr 3;9(4):1014. doi: 10.3390/jcm9041014. PMID: 32260182; PMCID: PMC7230878.","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50019"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16269"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50019"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T10:48:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T09:38:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8960"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64585"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relation